Machy (2022-02-05T21:02:27.676Z): an alief is an idea that, while not considered to be true, nonetheless garners a strong emotional reaction. Like jumping at shadows after watching a horror movie: you believe there's nothing to be scared of, but you're scared anyway. The notion that there's a monster in those shadows is an example of an alief.

boq Â± `en` @Isi #oPKFOa9-4 2024-09-08T12:35:12.910Z
predicate: â€˜preventâ€™; â–¯ prevents â–¯ from happening.
Isi (2024-09-08T13:08:31.982Z): The first slot is a thing and the second is an event.
Isi (2024-09-08T13:08:37.805Z): The idea behind these slots being this way: (1) I feel that there's not a big difference between a proposition or event preventing something from happening vs. a thing preventing it from happening. (2) It's possible to prevent a single event from happening but not preventing a different event from making the proposition true; e.g. you could prevent someone's death (by curing their disease), but then they die anyways (for unrelated reasons).
Isi (2024-09-08T13:08:43.452Z): Though I'm not sure if the semantics make sense when you refer to an event that doesn't actually happen.

â–¯ is one's communicative identifier/signature; â–¯ is one's "voice" (not necessarily vocal)
seaqtaq (2023-03-08T11:08:04.144Z): This is an abstraction of english's "voice" across every possible communicative medium, be it sound waves, the electromagnetic spectrum, tactile, olfactory, etc. Intended to be less anthropocentric, as the existence of this word means that it is not necessary to use the metaphor of "voice" to attempt to refer to communicative signatures in general. In addition to being less anthropocentric, it can be used for humans that can't speak as well. The word could be used to refer to the visual pecularities and idiosyncracies of the way one signs a particular sign language as well

prefix: combine two verbs into a verbâ€“object compound where the action denoted by the verb is specialized by the class of object
uakci (2023-08-12T15:38:58.769Z): in other words, **A gá»-B** is a kind of **A** specific to **B**-s. for example, if A = â€˜to sit sbâ€™ and B = â€˜babyâ€™, then A **gá»-**B would mean babysitting, or the kind of sitting thatâ€™s specific to babies

mimiaoganhaqpy (2024-09-18T06:30:18.250Z): As for your note that this word doesnâ€™t mention gender anywhere, the alternative would be heojeqda[mai/romantic-attract/sexual-attract]. You could think of this word as an shortening of that word. Additionally, Toaq compounds are not always just their parts combined. For example, choÄ±shoaÄ± means hawk, but it is a compound word â€œsharp-wingâ€
mimiaoganhaqpy (2024-09-18T06:31:25.218Z): Oh, and @maigoi, the word **heoseaq** exists for heterosexual.
mimiaoganhaqpy (2024-09-18T06:34:50.334Z): Additionally, you are free to coin new words as you like.  Most words in Toaq are created by the community based on need. â–¯ is a calorie/kilocalorie.
jiqci (2023-06-22T20:01:14.321Z): there were historically two calories, the large calorie being the amount of energy required to heat 1kg of water by 1 degree, and the small calorie being 1/1000th of that, i.e. heat required for 1-degree change of 1g of water. The term "calorie" nowadays refers to the large calorie, while "kilocalorie" means 1000 of the small calories, i.e. the two are equivalent.

What satisfies property â–¯ is independent of what satisfies property â–¯
fagri (2019-12-25T23:53:07.622Z): In other words, there are no ordered pairs (A, B) that are forbidden from satisfying the properties (P1, P2), unless A is always forbidden from satisfying P1 or B is always forbidden from satisfying P2
fagri (2019-12-25T23:53:40.240Z): Another way of saying the same thing is that the ordered pairs (A, B) that can satisfy (P1, P2) are simply the cross product of the values A that can satisfy P1 and the values B that can satisfy P2

uakci (2023-10-13T09:38:53.112Z): see **meq**, **kueu**. the mechanics of this word goes as follows: â€¢if X is binary, then the focus prefix feeds the focused part of a proposition as the first argument and the â€˜remainderâ€™ expressed as a lambda as the second argument. for example, **cho jÃ­ máº¹Ìqsoq sÃºq** transforms into **soq sÃºq, lÃ¤ cho jÃ­ jÃ¡**. in this vein, **máº¹Ìq'Ä±q** corresponds to the no-op focus prefix. note that the original preposition is lifted, i.e., no longer asserted (in favor of the ancillary proposition whose predicate is X); â€¢if X is unary, then the use of the focus prefix is equivalent to an adjoined clause with it replaced by **kÃº** â€“ for example, **cho jÃ­ máº¹ÌqgÄ±faq sÃºq** transforms into **cho jÃ­ sÃºq; gÄ±faq, ê¡Ã¤ cho jÃ® kÃº sÃºq**. note that this use is essentially similar to an eventive adverb (here, **gÃ®faq**), so like a focused/scoped adverbial if you will

Ilmen (2020-01-10T22:21:45.283Z): ``má»§Ä±dÅ«a meq ná»a nÃ­`` = ``ná»a mÃ»Ä±dÅ«a ja nÃ­``.

It is implied with paqsuim that there is a degree of control and care taken as to how the affected entity is broken apart

uakci (2022-01-09T14:49:46.970Z): actually, Â»despiteÂ« isnâ€™t even the right word here. the complement of a **soq** serial can be attributive or predicative. if itâ€™s predicative (say, A B), then **soq** sees the property of satisfying A the most (while also being B); if attributive, we still get valid semantics for things like **nuÄ± káº£nÄ±** â€˜small rabbitâ€™, since the **nuÄ±**-est **káº£nÄ±** is also the **nuÄ±**-est thing that is also a **kanÄ±**
uakci (2022-01-09T14:51:14.748Z): in other words, since the extent of an adjectival serial A B is proportional to the extent of A and not A Ã— B (barring situations where B is flat-out false), **soq** will look at the correct Â»partÂ« of the serial
uakci (2022-01-09T14:53:06.459Z): yet another way to look at it: in an adjectival serial such as A B, the A part is qualitative (how *much* something is A), whereas the B part is quantitative (*if* that thing is B *at all*). so rather than A Ã— B we have something like the *truth value* of B times the *extent* of Aa
uakci (2022-01-09T14:53:29.079Z): if you agree with these postulates, you'll find this definition of **soq** unobjectionable

ê Ã¤ tÄ± sÃºq nÃ­, bÃ¯ jaÄ± jÃ­. Â± `en` @robintown #sL7_nzMNF 2023-10-29T21:00:15.314Z
I'm happy that you're here.
robintown (2023-10-30T00:16:31.940Z): Lynn and I had a discussion about this, where we concluded that neither **kÃ»Ä±** or **gÃªm** really make sense for this meaning. As adjuncts, both constructions imply that you are, on the whole, happy. But imagine a situation in which you're having a bad day, and a friend comes to comfort you: you might say "I'm happy that you're here" even if it wouldn't be genuine to say "I'm happy". We found a paper https://www.semanticsarchive.net/Archive/DIzYWZkM/clauses.doc which claims that the clausal constituent participates in the semantics by a "regarding" relation, which suggests that a topic is the appropriate construction in Toaq. And there's similar evidence in Japanese to support this.
